# Vibe Test — Cursor Rules

This is the **vibe-test** source repository (the MCP server + CLI tool for browser testing).

## Project Overview

vibe-test is published as an npm package (`npx vibe-test`) and provides 12 MCP tools for AI-powered browser testing via Playwright. Users run `npx vibe-test init` in their project and then their AI editor can test their app.

## Architecture

- `src/cli.ts` — CLI entry + MCP server launcher (`--mcp` flag)
- `src/mcp-server.ts` — 12 MCP tools via JSON-RPC stdio
- `src/engine/context/` — Static code analysis (framework detection, route parsing, scenario generation)
- `src/engine/browser/` — Playwright execution (runner, explorer, verifier)
- `src/engine/memory/` — Persistent learning across runs
- `src/engine/reporter/` — HTML report generation

## When editing this repo

- TypeScript strict mode, ESM modules (`"type": "module"` in package.json)
- Build: `npm run build` (tsc → dist/)
- The MCP server communicates over stdio — all output must go to stderr or be MCP JSON-RPC responses
- Tool handlers are in `mcp-server.ts` — add new tools by: (1) adding to `ListToolsRequestSchema` handler, (2) adding to `CallToolRequestSchema` switch, (3) implementing the handler function
- `get_context` tool is the most important — it returns source files with relevance scoring so the LLM knows real selectors

## Key patterns

- Session state between MCP tool calls: `session` object in `mcp-server.ts`
- Framework detection: `detector.ts` — add new frameworks here
- Port auto-detection: `detectBaseUrl()` in `detector.ts`
- Monorepo support: `detectMonorepo()` + `findFrontendApp()` in `detector.ts`
- Init templates: the string constants at the top of `cli.ts` — these get written to user projects

## Publishing

Package name: `vibe-test`. Build → `npm publish`.
